"about 1450":"大约1450年","1427":"1427年","Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales":"威尔士蒙姆爾阿加文尼","Cardiff, Glamorgan, Wales":"威尔士格拉莫爾根卡迪福","Wales":"威尔士","Penarth, Glamorgan, Wales":"威尔士格拉莫爾根納特","lifeSummary":"当Joan verch John于大约1450年出生在威尔士蒙姆爾阿加文尼时，她的父亲John ap Rhys25岁，母亲Julian ferch Thomas21岁。她和Sion ap Gwilym至少有2个儿子。她去世于1489年在威尔士格拉莫爾根卡迪福享年40岁。"},"hr":{"about 1450–1489":"oko 1450.–1489.","1450–1489":"1450–1489.","1472–Male":"1472–preminuo","1475–Male":"1475–preminuo","1450–Male":"1450–preminuo","1479–Male":"1479.–preminuo","1485–Male":"1485–preminuo","1427–Male":"1427–preminuo","1430–Female":"1430–preminula","1479":"1479.","1489":"1489.","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1472":"1472","1450":"1450","abt 1485":"oko 1485.","about 1450":"oko 1450.","1427":"1427","Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales","Cardiff, Glamorgan, Wales":"Cardiff, Glamorgan, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Penarth, Glamorgan, Wales":"Penarth, Glamorgan, Wales"},"cs":{"about 1450–1489":"okolo 1450–1489","1450–1489":"1450–1489","1472–Male":"1472–Zesnulý","1475–Male":"1475–Zesnulý","1450–Male":"1450–Zesnulý","1479–Male":"1479–Zesnulý","1485–Male":"1485–Zesnulý","1427–Male":"1427–Zesnulý","1430–Female":"1430–Zesnulá","1479":"1479","1489":"1489","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1472":"1472","1450":"1450","abt 1485":"okolo 1485","about 1450":"okolo 1450","1427":"1427","Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales","Cardiff, Glamorgan, Wales":"Cardiff, Glamorgan, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Penarth, Glamorgan, Wales":"Penarth, Glamorgan, Wales"},"da":{"about 1450–1489":"omkring 1450–1489","1450–1489":"1450–1489","1472–Male":"1472–Afdød","1475–Male":"1475–Afdød","1450–Male":"1450–Afdød","1479–Male":"1479–Afdød","1485–Male":"1485–Afdød","1427–Male":"1427–Afdød","1430–Female":"1430–Afdød","1479":"1479","1489":"1489","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1472":"1472","1450":"1450","abt 1485":"omkring 1485","about 1450":"omkring 1450","1427":"1427","Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales","Cardiff, Glamorgan, Wales":"Cardiff, Glamorgan, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Penarth, Glamorgan, Wales":"Penarth, Glamorgan, Wales"},"nl":{"about 1450–1489":"circa 1450–1489","1450–1489":"1450–1489","1472–Male":"1472–Overleden","1475–Male":"1475–Overleden","1450–Male":"1450–Overleden","1479–Male":"1479–Overleden","1485–Male":"1485–Overleden","1427–Male":"1427–Overleden","1430–Female":"1430–Overleden","1479":"1479","1489":"1489","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1472":"1472","1450":"1450","abt 1485":"circa 1485","about 1450":"circa 1450","1427":"1427","Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales","Cardiff, Glamorgan, Wales":"Cardiff, Glamorgan, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Penarth, Glamorgan, Wales":"Penarth, Glamorgan, Wales"},"en":{"about 1450–1489":"about 1450–1489","1450–1489":"1450–1489","1472–Male":"1472–Deceased","1475–Male":"1475–Deceased","1450–Male":"1450–Deceased","1479–Male":"1479–Deceased","1485–Male":"1485–Deceased","1427–Male":"1427–Deceased","1430–Female":"1430–Deceased","1479":"1479","1489":"1489","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1472":"1472","1450":"1450","abt 1485":"about 1485","about 1450":"about 1450","1427":"1427","Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales","Cardiff, Glamorgan, Wales":"Cardiff, Glamorgan, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Penarth, Glamorgan, Wales":"Penarth, Glamorgan, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"John","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Welsh: ultimately from the Hebrew personal name <i>Yoḥanan</i> ‘Jehovah has favored (me with a son)’ or ‘may Jehovah favor (this child)’. This personal name was adopted into Latin (via Greek) as <i>Johannes</i>, and has enjoyed enormous popularity in Europe throughout the Christian era, being given in honor of Saint John the Baptist, precursor of Christ, and of Saint John the Evangelist, author of the fourth gospel, as well as the nearly one thousand other Christian saints who bore the name. Some of the principal forms of the personal name in other languages are: Welsh <i>Ieuan</i>, <i>Evan</i>, <i>Siôn</i>, and <i>Ioan</i>; Scottish <i>Ia(i)n</i>; Irish <i>Séan</i>; German <i>Johann</i>, <i>Johannes</i>; Dutch and Slavic <i>Jan</i>; French <i>Jean</i>; Italian <i>Giovanni</i>; Spanish <i>Juan</i>; Portuguese <i>João</i>; Greek <i>Iōannēs</i> (vernacular <i>Giannis</i>, <i>Yannis</i>); Russian <i>Ivan</i>. There were a number of different forms of the name in Middle English, including <i>Jan(e)</i>, a male name (see   Jayne  ); <i>Jen</i> (see   Jenkin  ); <i>Jon(e)</i> (see   Jones  ); and <i>Han(n)</i> (see   Hann  ). By the beginning of the 14th century <i>John</i> rivalled <i>William</i> in popularity and has always been a favorite name. <i>Johan</i> became <i>Jo(h)n</i>, and another Old French form <i>Jehan</i> was shortened to <i>Jan</i> and <i>Jen</i>, giving rise to Old French and Middle English diminutives such as <i>Jonin</i>, <i>Janin</i>, and <i>Jenin</i>. More common in Middle English were <i>Jankin</i>, <i>Jonkin</i>, and <i>Jenkin</i>, which were Middle Dutch pet forms introduced after the Conquest by Flemish and Picard settlers. The most common pet form of John was <i>Jack</i>, another borrowing from Flemish and Picard usage. <i>Han</i> may sometimes have been a short form of <i>Johan</i> but was more usually a pet form of Henry. There were also various Middle English feminine versions of this name (e.g. <i>Joan</i>, <i>Jehan</i>), some of which were indistinguishable from masculine forms. The distinction on grounds of gender between <i>John</i> and <i>Joan</i> was not firmly established in English until the 17th century. It was even later that <i>Jean</i> and <i>Jane</i> were specialized as specifically female names in English; bearers of these surnames and their derivatives are more likely to derive them from a male ancestor than a female. As a surname in the British Isles, <i>John</i> is particularly frequent in Wales, where it is a late formation representing Welsh <i>Siôn</i> rather than the older form <i>Ieuan</i> (which gave rise to the surname   Evan  ). In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages, e.g. Assyrian/Chaldean   Youkhana  , French   Jean  , Hungarian <b>János</b> (see   Janos  ), Slovenian <b>Janež</b> and <b>Janeš</b> (see   Janes  ), Czech   Jan  , Albanian   Gjoni  , and their derivatives (see examples at   Johnson  ). The name <i>John</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Ninan   and   Yohannan  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US.","German: from a North German and Silesian variant of the personal name   Johannes  . This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine). Compare   Yohn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ancar","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Francois, Alphonse, Etienne, Fabien, Mireille.","Probably an altered form of French (Pas-de-Calais, Nord) <b>Ancart</b>, itself a variant of <b>Hancart</b> and <b>Hanecart</b>: from a pet form (double diminutive) of the personal name <i>Han</i>, a short form of French <i>Jehan</i> and Flemish <i>Johan(nes)</i> (see   John  )."]},{"name":"Bongiovanni","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Mario, Antonio, Dante, Salvatore, Santo, Antonino, Domenic, Gaetano, Geno, Giacomo, Gilda, Luciano, Nino.","Italian: from a personal name composed of the elements <i>bon</i> ‘good’ + <i>Giovanni</i>, an equivalent of   John  ."]},{"name":"Di Giovanna","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Gaspar, Alfonso, Carlo, Domenic, Gaetano, Liborio, Nunzio, Pietro, Rosario, Sal, Salvatore.","Italian: metronymic from the female personal name <i>Giovanna</i>, an equivalent of <i>Joan</i> (see   John  )."]},{"name":"Anes","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Angel, Dionisio, Esperanza, Gilberto, Ines, Juanita, Luis, Luisa, Manuel, Manuela, Pedro.  Portuguese Joao.","Portuguese and Galician: patronymic from a shortened form of the Latin personal name <i>Johannes</i> (Portuguese <i>João</i>, Galician <i>Xoán</i>; see   John  )."]},{"name":"Burhans","meanings":["German: from Middle Low German <i>būr</i> ‘farmer, peasant’ + the personal name <i>Hans</i>, a short form of <i>Johannes</i> (see   John  ), hence a distinguishing occupational name ‘farmer John’ with <i>Hans</i> being a very frequent name. See also   Burian  ."]},{"name":"Breihan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Kurt.","German: distinguishing nickname for a (beer) brewer, from Middle High German <i>briuw(er)</i> ‘brew(er)’ + a short form of the personal name <i>Johann(es)</i> (see   John  )."]},{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire) and Welsh (Monmouthshire): from the Middle English male personal name <i>Jan(e)</i>, from Old French <i>Jehan</i>, a variant of <i>Johan</i>, which gave rise to the common alternative   John  . Sometimes the name may also arise from the Welsh variant <i>Ieun</i> of Welsh <i>Ieuan</i>, likewise equivalent to   John   (compare   Evan  )."]},{"name":"Di Giovanni","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Vito, Rocco, Sal, Aldo, Carlo, Gino, Giuseppe, Guido, Agostino, Carmela.","Italian: patronymic from the personal name <i>Giovanni</i>, an equivalent of   John  . Compare   De Giovanni  ,   Dejohn  , and   Giovanni  ."]},{"name":"Eanes","meanings":["English (Hampshire): probably a variant of <b>Heanes</b> with loss of initial <i>H-</i>, itself a variant of <b>Heane</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, a nickname from Middle English <i>hen(e)</i>, <i>heine</i> ‘poor, needy, wretched’ (Old English <i>hēan</i>). <i>Eanes</i> is now rare in Britain, and in the US is found predominantly in VA.","Portuguese and Galician: patronymic from the Latin personal name <i>Johannes</i> (Portuguese <i>João</i>, Galician <i>Xoán</i>; see   John  )."]},{"name":"Ene","meanings":["Romanian: from a derivative of the personal name <i>Ioan</i> (see   John  ).","West African (Nigeria): unexplained."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]},{"name":"verch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Orlo.","German: variant of   Ferch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferch","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan verch John was born about 1450, in Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales, her father, John ap Rhys, was 25 and her mother, Julian ferch Thomas, was 21. She had at least 2 sons with Sion ap Gwilym. She died in 1489, in Cardiff, Glamorgan, Wales, at the age of 40."},"et":{"about 1450–1489":"umbes 1450–1489","1450–1489":"1450–1489","1472–Male":"1472–Surnud","1475–Male":"1475–Surnud","1450–Male":"1450–Surnud","1479–Male":"1479–Surnud","1485–Male":"1485–Surnud","1427–Male":"1427–Surnud","1430–Female":"1430–Surnud","1479":"1479","1489":"1489","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1472":"1472","1450":"1450","abt 1485":"umbes 1485","about 1450":"umbes 1450","1427":"1427","Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales","Cardiff, Glamorgan, Wales":"Cardiff, Glamorgan, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Penarth, Glamorgan, Wales":"Penarth, Glamorgan, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1450–1489":"noin 1450–1489","1450–1489":"1450–1489","1472–Male":"1472–Kuollut","1475–Male":"1475–Kuollut","1450–Male":"1450–Kuollut","1479–Male":"1479–Kuollut","1485–Male":"1485–Kuollut","1427–Male":"1427–Kuollut","1430–Female":"1430–Kuollut","1479":"1479","1489":"1489","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1472":"1472","1450":"1450","abt 1485":"noin 1485","about 1450":"noin 1450","1427":"1427","Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales","Cardiff, Glamorgan, Wales":"Cardiff, Glamorgan, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Penarth, Glamorgan, Wales":"Penarth, Glamorgan, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1450–1489":"environ 1450–1489","1450–1489":"145